S-N-S, and the fan-out pattern.

S-N-S is a fully managed pub/sub service. The model is one-to-many: a publisher sends a message to a topic, and S-N-S delivers a copy to every subscriber simultaneously. Unlike S-Q-S, there's no queue; once delivered, the message is gone from S-N-S's perspective, so persistence is the subscriber's job. Subscribers can be S-Q-S queues, which is by far the most common and turns S-N-S into a persistent fan-out; Lambda functions; H-T-T-P or H-T-T-P-S webhooks; email, S-M-S, or mobile push; or Kinesis Data Firehose, for delivery into S3, Redshift, or OpenSearch. A single topic can have up to twelve and a half million subscriptions, and messages cap at two hundred fifty-six kilobytes. Filter policies let each subscriber declare what it cares about, by attributes or the message body, so it only receives matching messages instead of every one.

The S-N-S-plus-S-Q-S fan-out is the most reused pattern in AWS messaging. One event needs to reach several downstream systems, each at its own pace, each with its own retry behaviour. Publishing directly to multiple S-Q-S queues would couple the producer to the fan-out topology: add a consumer, and you change the producer; one queue write fails, and you get partial delivery. Instead: the producer publishes once to an S-N-S topic; S-N-S delivers to each subscribed S-Q-S queue; and each queue feeds an independent consumer, with its own D-L-Q, visibility timeout, and scaling.

The producer doesn't know who's downstream. Adding a new consumer is one new S-Q-S queue and one new S-N-S subscription, with no producer change, and each consumer survives its peers' failures because the queues are independent. The canonical case: an order placement that has to email the customer, charge the card, reserve inventory, and notify shipping.
